revision.text:
'''目'''（さかん）とは、日本の[[律令制]][[四等官]]のうち四等官を指す。

「目」の文字は[[国司]]の四等官（中央政府における「[[主典]]」に相当する）を指す。主に、官事の記録及び公文の草案作成等を掌った。特に[[大国]]と呼ばれる最上級の[[令制国]]には特に[[大目]]・[[少目]]が設置された。
{{DEFAULTSORT:さかん}}
[[Category:律令制の官制]]
{{Japanese-history-stub}}

'''Sakan''' (目) refers to the fourth rank officer (equivalent to "Shuten" in the central government) under the [[Four-Rank System]] of [[Kokushi]] (provincial governors) during Japan's [[Ritsuryō system]].
In the medieval and early modern periods, it came to be used as an honorary title granted by the imperial court or imperial households to artisans and performers.
== Title of Kokushi == The four-rank officers of Kokushi were designated as [[Kami]] (守), [[Suke]] (介), [[Jō]] (掾), and '''Sakan''' (目). Sakan primarily managed the recording of official matters and drafting of public documents.
Under the rules set forth in the {{ill|Taihō Code|ja|大宝令|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Yōrō Code|ja|養老令|12=draft|12=draft}}, the provincial administration system varied according to the size and resources of a [[Provinces of Japan#Ritsuryō classification|province]]. In [[China (Ritsuryō province)|middle-ranked provinces]] or [[Shimo provinces|lower-ranked provinces]], certain offices such as Suke and Jō were omitted, but Sakan was still a11ointed. Conversely, [[Daikoku (Ritsuryō provinces)|large provinces]] were given two Sakan ranks, known as {{ill|Ōsakan|ja|大目|12=draft|12=draft}} (chief Sakan) and {{ill|Shōsakan|ja|少目|12=draft|12=draft}} (deputy Sakan).
In practice, however, the number of personnel fluctuated. Even in middle-ranked provinces, Ōsakan and Shōsakan could be a11ointed (see {{ill|Kokushi#Classification of Provinces|ja|国司#国等級区分|12=draft|12=draft}}).
== Honorary Titles for Artisans and Performers == The title of Sakan, originally used in the Ritsuryō system for provincial administration, was later adopted as an honorary designation for artisans, merchants, swordsmiths, and performers such as {{ill|jōruri|ja|浄瑠璃|12=draft|12=draft}} artists. This was done to honor their skills and accomplishments.<ref>Yasuda Fumiko, "Kinsei Juryō Kō," in *Kojōruri Seihon* (Kadokawa Shoten, 1967).</ref> Similar practices were observed for other Kokushi ranks, such as {{ill|Jō|ja|掾|12=draft|12=draft}}.
=== Jōruri === One notable example in Jōruri is the case of Fujiwara no Sadakatsu, who was granted the rank of {{ill|Senior Sixth Rank, Lower Grade|ja|正六位下|1=Senior Sixth Rank|lt=Senior Sixth Rank, Lower Grade|12=draft|12=draft}} as "Echigo Sakan" (越後の目) in 1663 (Kanbun 3). He later became known as Tsuma no Tayū (都万大夫).<ref>Records from *Jōruri Tayū Kuchisengen* and *Karasumaru Family Notes*.</ref> Another example is Sado no Masayoshi, who was granted the rank of {{ill|Junior Sixth Rank, Lower Grade|ja|従六位下|1=Junior Sixth Rank|lt=Junior Sixth Rank, Lower Grade|12=draft|12=draft}} as "Sado Sakan" (佐渡の目) and later became known as Sadojima no Masayoshi.
== Notes == === Annotations === {{notelist}}
=== References === {{reflist}} == See Also == * {{ill|Mokudai|ja|目代|12=draft|12=draft}}
{{Japanese-history-stub}}
