'''Sakan''' (目) refers to the fourth Rank officer (equivalent to "Shuten" in the central government) under the [[Four-Rank System]] of [[Kokushi]] (provincial governors) during Japan's [[Ritsuryō system]].
In the medieval and early modern periods, it came to be used as an honorary title granted by the imperial court or imperial households to artisans and performers.
== Title of Kokushi == The four-Rank officers of Kokushi were designated as [[Kami]] (守), [[Suke]] (介), [[:en:Jō|Jō]] (掾), and '''Sakan''' (目). Sakan primarily managed the recording of official matters and drafting of public documents.
Under the rules set forth in the {{ill|Taihō Code|ja|大宝令|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taihō Code|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 大宝律令}} and {{ill|Yōrō Code|ja|養老令|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yōrō Code|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 養老律令}}, the provincial administration system varied according to the size and resources of a [[Provinces of Japan#Ritsuryō classification|province]]. In [[China (Ritsuryō province)|middle-Ranked provinces]] or [[Shimo provinces|lower-Ranked provinces]], certain offices such as Suke and Jō were omitted, but Sakan was still a11ointed. Conversely, [[Daikoku (Ritsuryō provinces)|large provinces]] were given two Sakan Ranks, known as {{ill|Ōsakan|ja|大目|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōsakan|qq=}} (chief Sakan) and {{ill|Shōsakan|ja|少目|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōsakan|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 目 (国司)}} (deputy Sakan).
In practice, however, the number of personnel fluctuated. Even in middle-Ranked provinces, Ōsakan and Shōsakan could be a11ointed (see {{ill|Kokushi#Classification of Provinces|ja|国司#国等級区分|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kokushi#Classification of Provinces|qq=}}).
== Honorary Titles for Artisans and Performers == The title of Sakan, originally used in the Ritsuryō system for provincial administration, was later adopted as an honorary designation for artisans, merchants, swordsmiths, and performers such as [[:en:Jōruri (music)|jōruri]] artists. This was done to honor their skills and accomplishments.<ref>Yasuda Fumiko, "Kinsei Juryō Kō," in *Kojōruri Seihon* (Kadokawa Shoten, 1967).</ref> Similar practices were observed for other Kokushi Ranks, such as {{ill|Jō|ja|掾|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jō|qq=}}.
=== Jōruri === One notable example in Jōruri is the case of Fujiwara no Sadakatsu, who was granted the Rank of {{ill|Senior Sixth Rank, Lower Grade|ja|正六位下|1=Senior Sixth Rank|lt=Senior Sixth Rank, Lower Grade|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Senior Sixth Rank, Lower Grade|13=User:Immanuelle/Senior Sixth Rank|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 正六位}} as "Echigo Sakan" (越後の目) in 1663 (Kanbun 3). He later became known as Tsuma no Tayū (都万大夫).<ref>Records from *Jōruri Tayū Kuchisengen* and *Karasumaru Family Notes*.</ref> Another example is Sado no Masayoshi, who was granted the Rank of {{ill|Junior Sixth Rank, Lower Grade|ja|従六位下|1=Junior Sixth Rank|lt=Junior Sixth Rank, Lower Grade|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Junior Sixth Rank, Lower Grade|13=User:Immanuelle/Junior Sixth Rank|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 従六位}} as "Sado Sakan" (佐渡の目) and later became known as Sadojima no Masayoshi.
